\details{
Contiguity neighbours are detected with \code{\link[spdep:poly2nb]{spdep::poly2nb()}}, which supports
both Queen (default, shared edge \strong{or} vertex) and Rook (shared edge only)
contiguity. Municipalities that share no boundary ("spatial islands") are
automatically detected and reported. The resulting neighbour list is
normalised to a \code{listw} object via \code{\link[spdep:nb2listw]{spdep::nb2listw()}}.
}
\section{Snap distance}{

Municipal boundaries digitised at different scales often have small gaps or
overlaps at shared borders. The \code{snap} argument passes a distance tolerance
(in the units of the CRS) to \code{\link[spdep:poly2nb]{spdep::poly2nb()}}: any two polygon boundaries
within \code{snap} distance are treated as touching. The default (\code{NULL}) uses
\code{1e-3} (appropriate for degree-based CRS such as EPSG:4674 / SIRGAS2000).
For projected CRS (metres) consider values around \code{1} to \code{100}.
}

\section{Weight styles}{

\itemize{
\item \code{"W"} (default) — row-standardised: each neighbour weight = 1/n_neighbours
\item \code{"B"} — binary: 1 if neighbour, 0 otherwise
\item \code{"C"} — globally standardised
\item \code{"U"} — equal to \code{"C"} divided by number of neighbours
\item \code{"S"} — variance-stabilising (Tiefelsdorf et al. 1999)
\item \code{"minmax"} — min/max normalisation
}
}

\examples{
\dontrun{
library(geobr)
library(climasus4r)

# Download Nordeste municipalities (SIRGAS2000 / EPSG:4674)
muni <- geobr::read_municipality(code_muni = "all", year = 2022)
muni_ne <- muni[muni$abbrev_state \%in\% c("CE","RN","PB","PE","AL",
                                         "SE","BA","PI","MA"), ]

# Row-standardised Queen contiguity (default)
w <- sus_mod_spatial_weights(muni_ne)
print(w)

# Binary Rook weights, returning the dense W matrix
w_rook <- sus_mod_spatial_weights(
  municipalities = muni_ne,
  style          = "B",
  queen          = FALSE,
  return_matrix  = TRUE
)
dim(w_rook$W)
}

}
